<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-355-608  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 355 608.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  April 5 1990 n1208 p36(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Putting geography on the map: geographic information systemscombine digital maps with databases.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>McKay, Ian.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Geographic information systems (GISs), which combine digital mapswith computer databases of geographic data, are expected to extendcartographic applications, but professional cartographers areconcerned for the impact of GISs on the quality of their craft.andO;The spread of GISs to low-cost computer hardware and the abilityof GISs to juxtapose data that have never been related before aredriving the growth in applications.andP;  These applications includeenvironmental planning, analyses of census statistics for anydefined area, compilation of demographic databases, and vehiclenavigation systems.andP;  Current cartographic systems are beingdigitized, as exemplified by the conversion and marketing of theUK's Ordnance Survey Maps as Superplans.andP;  The data is being usedby such companies as Pinpoint, the leading GIS vendor in the UK.andO;Development of vehicle navigation systems is briefly discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Geographic Information SystemsProduct DevelopmentTrendsUnited KingdomProductsApplicationsManufacturers.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>